Shifting 20% to second bucket. 45

Re-assessing a bit in favour of the Democrats. One key point seems to be that many women are now registering to vote (https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-08-30/women-s-voter-sign-ups-surge-after-roe-ruling-buoying-democrats). Turnout is usually lower for midterms than for presidential elections (45-50% against 60%+ for presidential elections) so a surge in turnout from newly registered women voters could make a significant difference. Moreover, past polls that focus on registered voters will not be representative if the voter demographic changes. Still, there's still some time to go and many things could happen that could shift votes either way.

I also think the Roe decision will end up having an impact, but I want to see if the anger and rage remain this high all through summer.

At a glance, 221 +/-

Initial forecast based on current polls (https://www.270towin.com/2022-house-election/) that show a lower bound of 208 seats and an upper bound of 237 seats for the Republicans. This is consistent with recent trends (https://ballotpedia.org/United_States_Congress_elections,_2022).

the 2010 midterms saw R have a net-gain of 63 seats - similar political environment currently - that would be R with 272 seats in the house; similar R lost 42 seats in the 2018 midterms; since 1997 - D's have held as avg of 212 seats (highest 235, lowest 188) and R's with an average of 222 (highest 247, lowest 178) - given that, i think a good chance of picking up seats in the 229-239 range, potentially in the 240-250 - anything beyond that would be an outlier
